LXXXVIII. Epitaph on a young slave of Martial buried somewhere on the Labican Road. The via Labicana began, as did also the via Praenestina and the via Valeria or Tiburtina, from the Esquiline gate. It ran past the Labicmm (La Colon- na fifteen miles from Rome), and leavmg this on its right proceeded to Ad Pictas where it joined the Latin Road, see Burn. R. and C. pp. 381—437. Schneidewin in both editions adopts the spelling Lavicana which appears to have the best MSS. authority in its favour. Perhaps the quantity may have had something to do with Martial's choice of this form. The a of Labicum is usually short, Virg. Aen. vn. 796 picti scuta
